  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Another Letter of Hand-Written Words Sent to Master An
  author: Lee Gyu-bo
  language: eng
  text: |-
    On this day of the month, I write to you with utmost respect.

    Regarding the brush ink you so kindly procured for me through an intermediary—I am deeply mortified at having troubled you with such a trifling matter, and anxiously await whatever censure may be due. Yet through your generosity, I have received several scrolls of wind-brushed bamboo. When that person brought them to show me, he conveyed your thanks with such sincerity that it moved my heart. Observing how the branches and leaves seem alive with motion, I imagined I could hear the refreshing whisper of rustling wind through them—truly, you have captured the very essence of bamboo dancing in the breeze. When I once compared you to a gentleman of refined letters, I now see my words were well-aimed indeed.

    Further, you humbly press me for my recent verses and prose. Though I confess a lifelong love of poetry, I remain a man perpetually harried by military duties. Moreover, having dwelt among tigers and leopards, should I openly delight in composing and chanting, I would surely incur the contempt of the multitude. Thus my output has been sparse. What little I have written is soon spirited away by others—my boxes contain not a single page remaining. As for the rest, they are merely formal prayers to Buddha and sacrificial verses to the gods, hardly worthy of your refined attention. Therefore I dare not presume to send them. I beg you take no offense at this refusal.

    With winter's chill approaching, I humbly pray you cherish yourself and remain in good health. I remain your devoted servant.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: 'Brush ink (墨君): A respectful way of referring to ink, showing the refined aesthetic sensibility of the literati.'
  - key: ''
    value: 'Wind-brushed bamboo (風竹): A reference to paintings of bamboo, a favorite subject in East Asian literati art, symbolizing integrity and resilience.'
  - key: ''
    value: 'A gentleman of refined letters (文洋州): A classical allusion praising the recipient''s scholarly accomplishments.'
  - key: ''
    value: 'Tigers and leopards: A metaphorical reference to the violent military environment and court intrigues in which the author served.'
